Day Ten Reflection – Inter-VLAN Routing

On day ten, I learnt about Inter-VLAN Routing and how devices in different VLANs communicate with each other. The lesson focused on the operation of Inter-VLAN Routing, Router-on-a-Stick configuration, Layer 3 switching, and troubleshooting routing issues in VLAN environments.

Topics Covered and What I Learnt
4.1 Inter-VLAN Routing Operation
1. What is Inter-VLAN Routing?

I learnt that Inter-VLAN Routing is the process that allows devices in different VLANs to communicate with one another through a routing device. I understood that:

VLANs separate broadcast domains
Devices in different VLANs cannot communicate directly
A router or Layer 3 switch is required for communication between VLANs

This topic helped me understand how network segmentation works while still allowing controlled communication.

2. Legacy Inter-VLAN Routing

I learnt about the traditional method of Inter-VLAN Routing where:

Each VLAN connects to a separate physical router interface
Multiple physical connections are required
The method is less scalable in modern networks

This helped me understand the limitations of older routing designs.

3. Router-on-a-Stick Inter-VLAN Routing

I learnt about Router-on-a-Stick, where:

A single router interface handles traffic from multiple VLANs
Subinterfaces are created for each VLAN
A trunk link connects the router to the switch

I understood that this method is more efficient and widely used in small to medium-sized networks.

4. Inter-VLAN Routing on a Layer 3 Switch

I learnt that Layer 3 switches can perform both switching and routing functions. I understood that:

Layer 3 switches route traffic between VLANs internally
Routing becomes faster because it happens within the switch
This method is commonly used in enterprise networks

This introduced me to modern high-performance network design.

